      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <date when="1822-02-23"/>23 February 1822</dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                            Dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss Edgeworth</persName>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p> You do me too much honour in supposing
                    me so deeply and personally interested in the
                    republication of the novels in question - Not so
                    the rest of your letter which gives me the agreeable
                    assurance that you &amp; the young ladies your sisters
                    are to visit <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#STK">Scotland</placeName> early in May &amp; will honor
                    <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Abbotsfsord-House_STK">Abbotsford</placeName> (never more honored) in the first weeks
                    of that month. Remember however this is only
                    your first visit otherwise we shall be strangely
                    defrauded as I must be in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edinburgh_STK">Edinburgh</placeName> on the
                    12[<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. when our Courts resume their sittings So I
                    <unclear/> know if we can combine to <unclear>when</unclear> Abbots
                    <unclear/> of <unclear/>
                    You will find me like a King (every busied with
                    pulling down &amp; building up - there is however enough
                    of lodging such as it is having an actual roof
                    on it for I had the sense to build half of my
                    
                    house before I pulled the rest down so we shall
                    be well enough though amid lime and dust &amp;
                    <unclear/> good <unclear>here</unclear>.
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotM1">Lady Scott</persName>
               <hi rend="underline">thof</hi>
               <unclear>M of</unclear> unknown offers her kind
                    respects and I am glad I shall have my daughter
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockS1">Sophia</persName> with me who as well as her <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotA1">younger sister</persName> &amp;
                    brothers is very eager to make your acquaintance
                    They are neither of them at all made up or <hi rend="underline">got</hi>
               <hi rend="underline">up</hi> and rather under than over educated I was so
                    terrified for their becoming <unclear>lionesses</unclear> at second hand
                    that I left them <del/> in a good measure to
                    their natural gifts - Both are naturally shrewd
                    &amp; sensible &amp; the elder has a sort of quiet and
                    sincere enthusiasm about her own country which
                    will entertain you Always with the greatest
                    truth &amp; respect <unclear/>
                    
                    trust me <unclear>with</unclear>
                    -ford tolerably agreeble the
                    you there again when the autumn <unclear>vacation</unclear> sits <del>on</del>
                    me <unclear>and</unclear> freedom for four months after 12 July
                    1822</p>
            <closer>
                    <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
